There is a heavy grind for gear to survive the next set of battles. Having only three songs in the game, catchy as they are, doesn`t help fight the monotony. However, with the grind also comes a sense of progression, until you can slaughter those op treants with ease. That said, when you do reach the goal, there is nothing else to do. Overall, it`s good, simple fun.

You can choose from many upgrades to increase your health, rewards, and combos. Should you get it? I think it would be great for a puzzle player. But I'm not too satisfied by it.

A simple match-three style game at first glance, plus a timing mechanic where certain tiles are needed to progress during each "run". Add in a base building mechanic and RPG elements and you got yourself an addictive package. Many developers would kill to make this fun and they would have monetized the hell out of it. This developer wisely decided not to. The price is more than worth it for a fun game with no ads, no freemium "pay to advance" mechanics constantly nagging you to spend real money for fake virtual currency and a real end game to work towards. I wish more games did this.

Doors require matching keys while enemies require matching swords or wands or shields. There's more to it than that but the size of these reviews don't allow much more elaboration. I recommend trying it out if you don't mind the length.

Match-3 meets RPG meets Endless Runner. That sums up 10000000 (Ten Million) in a nutshell. Slide tiles around with wrap-around and try to match items as quickly as possible to deal damage to enemies and stay on the screen. Slide off the left side and you lose. Get to the little checkered line on the right and stay ahead of it for a real rush: You start a counter of a certain resource, such as EXP or Gold. Stay across long enough for the counter to fill and you get that value of resources. Fall back behind the line and poof, they're gone. The graphics work well for what it's trying to be. The music... well, I'm slightly amazed that the main theme of the game is Creative Commons licensed, but it's awesome. For $2 you just can't go wrong. Only gripe is that acquiring gold was a little tedious at times. That improved once I rose in rank. That gripe isn't enough to make me deduct any ★s though. In short, if you enjoy blazing-fast Match-3 games, get 10000000.

A dangerously addictive combination of a compulsive match-3 puzzle game (e.g. Bejeweled, Candy Crush) and old-school dungeon crawling RPG (e.g. Gurk). Your player runs through an infinite dungeon and you must match 3 or more symbols to get past chests (match keys to unlock) and monsters (match swords or staves to slay). Each dungeon run lasts only a minute or two and then you are returned to your castle to level up using the loot you gained on your last run. Simple, fast and fiendishly addictive. It's mobile gaming perfection, plus there are no hidden fees which appears to be a rarity these days.

Had the chance to demo this game when it was first introduced to the Apple store for the iPhone, and it was a phenomenal hit.  The developer (a single individual) was then asked by the Android community for a port.  This occurs many times, and it's a shame that many Apple developers (many of whom have use of entire teams, and not a single person) choose not to do so, as it's simply "too hard."  This developer however, has sacrificed much of his free time (mostly by himself), in order to bring an awesome game over to our side of the fence.  The game itself is intuitive, insanely fun, and rabidly addictive, but even if it weren't, the customer service (and determination) of that magnitude is worth incredible respect and (at the very least) $1.99.  Thank you, EightyEight Games, and looking forward to seeing more of your work in the future!  :)

This is the perfect game to play on a cell phone. On it's surface, it's a shallow but fun puzzle game. You match objects in a slider puzzle to unlock chests, fight enemies and defend your character. But as you dig deeper, you unlock upgrades and enchantments to make your dungeon runs last longer. With each achievement you complete you gain experience and gold to spend however you like to strengthen your runs. As you last longer, more enemies and challenges appear keeping the game fresh and interesting. This game is fun to play in short chunks on a train ride, or for hours on the couch at home. Highly recommended.
